summing over all the possibilities.

2226
01:26:47,300 --> 01:26:53,300
So trace becomes,

2227
01:26:53,300 --> 01:27:01,300
or sum over configurations becomes trace.

2228
01:27:01,300 --> 01:27:05,300
You'll see how it works as we go along.

2229
01:27:05,300 --> 01:27:08,300
Now, there is a very similar

2230
01:27:08,300 --> 01:27:11,300
formula to this in quantum mechanics,

2231
01:27:11,300 --> 01:27:12,300
which of course,

2232
01:27:12,300 --> 01:27:14,300
involves a trace.

2233
01:27:14,300 --> 01:27:16,800
And the trial involves a

2234
01:27:16,800 --> 01:27:19,300
trace of the observable times something.

2235
01:27:19,300 --> 01:27:22,300
And that something is called the density matrix.

2236
01:27:22,300 --> 01:27:26,300
And I'm going to explain it to

2237
01:27:26,300 --> 01:27:30,300
you now in a very simple situation first.

2238
01:27:30,300 --> 01:27:37,300
Supposing somebody prepares a state of a system,

2239
01:27:37,300 --> 01:27:40,300
any one of the states of an orthonormal basis i,

2240
01:27:40,300 --> 01:27:43,300
behind your back,

2241
01:27:43,300 --> 01:27:49,300
somebody creates a system in some state i,

2242
01:27:49,300 --> 01:27:54,300
but doesn't tell you which state they've created it in.

2243
01:27:54,300 --> 01:27:56,300
So it's definitely an electron or

2244
01:27:56,300 --> 01:27:58,300
a spin or a composite system

2245
01:27:58,300 --> 01:28:00,300
or whatever it happens to be.

2246
01:28:00,300 --> 01:28:04,300
It's been created by somebody else in a particular state,

2247
01:28:04,300 --> 01:28:09,300
but all they have told you is a probability distribution

2248
01:28:09,300 --> 01:28:12,300
for what state they created the system in.

2249
01:28:12,300 --> 01:28:15,300
In other words, what we can

2250
01:28:15,300 --> 01:28:18,300
imagine is somebody creating an electron

2251
01:28:18,300 --> 01:28:21,300
by putting it into a magnetic field,

2252
01:28:21,300 --> 01:28:24,300
and that magnetic field could be up,

2253
01:28:24,300 --> 01:28:26,300
or it could be down.

2254
01:28:26,300 --> 01:28:28,300
And they tell you,

2255
01:28:28,300 --> 01:28:30,300
here's an electron,

2256
01:28:30,300 --> 01:28:31,800
it's either up or down, but

2257
01:28:31,800 --> 01:28:33,300
I'm not going to tell you which.

2258
01:28:33,300 --> 01:28:35,300
I'll give you a probability though,

2259
01:28:35,300 --> 01:28:38,300
75% likelihood that it's up,

2260
01:28:38,300 --> 01:28:41,300
25% likelihood that it's down.

2261
01:28:41,300 --> 01:28:44,300
This is not a situation where

2262
01:28:44,300 --> 01:28:47,300
you would write up plus down,

2263
01:28:47,300 --> 01:28:50,300
or even three quarters up plus one quarter down.

2264
01:28:50,300 --> 01:28:53,300
That's not right, but you know what I mean.

2265
01:28:53,300 --> 01:28:55,300
You wouldn't add the states together

2266
01:28:55,300 --> 01:28:57,300
at all with a definite phase.

2267
01:28:57,300 --> 01:28:59,300
You would just say you

2268
01:28:59,300 --> 01:29:01,300
don't know what state it's in,

2269
01:29:01,300 --> 01:29:05,300
and the system is described statistically

2270
01:29:05,300 --> 01:29:08,300
with a greater degree of statistics,

2271
01:29:08,300 --> 01:29:11,300
than if it had been in a,

2272
01:29:11,300 --> 01:29:13,300
than if you knew what state it was in.

2273
01:29:13,300 --> 01:29:15,300
Even if you knew what state it was in,

2274
01:29:15,300 --> 01:29:19,300
certain measurements would still be probabilistic.

2275
01:29:19,300 --> 01:29:20,800
If you knew what state it

2276
01:29:20,800 --> 01:29:22,300
was in, certain experiments might be definite,

2277
01:29:22,300 --> 01:29:24,300
and certain others might be probabilistic,

2278
01:29:24,300 --> 01:29:28,300
but here's an added degree of probability,

2279
01:29:28,300 --> 01:29:31,300
an added probability aspect of things,

2280
01:29:31,300 --> 01:29:32,800
that not only if the

2281
01:29:32,800 --> 01:29:34,300
system was in a definite state

2282
01:29:34,300 --> 01:29:37,300
might you not know the answer to every question,

2283
01:29:37,300 --> 01:29:38,800
but you might not even know

2284
01:29:38,800 --> 01:29:40,300
what state the system is in.

2285
01:29:40,300 --> 01:29:43,300
Under those circumstances, you use an object called

2286
01:29:43,300 --> 01:29:47,300
the density matrix instead of state vectors.

2287
01:29:47,300 --> 01:29:50,300
Density matrices are kind of a looser concept,

2288
01:29:50,300 --> 01:29:51,800
a concept when you don't know

2289
01:29:51,800 --> 01:29:53,300
what state the system is in,

2290
01:29:53,300 --> 01:29:56,300
and it's a probability distribution for different states.

2291
01:29:56,300 --> 01:29:59,300
Alright, so let's suppose that we have,

2292
01:29:59,300 --> 01:30:02,300
that somebody has prepared the system

2293
01:30:02,300 --> 01:30:06,300
definitely in one of the basis states, I,

2294
01:30:07,300 --> 01:30:11,300
with a probability, let's call it rho sub i.

2295
01:30:11,300 --> 01:30:14,300
I'm using rho now instead of p,

2296
01:30:14,300 --> 01:30:18,300
just because it's a standard convention for this situation,

2297
01:30:18,300 --> 01:30:20,300
to call it rho.

2298
01:30:20,300 --> 01:30:22,300
So that's the,

2299
01:30:22,300 --> 01:30:25,300
rho then is the probability for the i-th state.

2300
01:30:25,300 --> 01:30:28,300
Now we can make a matrix out of rho.

2301
01:30:28,300 --> 01:30:30,300
We can make a matrix out of rho,

2302
01:30:30,300 --> 01:30:31,800
and here's the way I'll

2303
01:30:31,800 --> 01:30:33,300
make a matrix out of rho.

2304
01:30:33,300 --> 01:30:36,300
I'm just going to, this is the matrix

2305
01:30:36,300 --> 01:30:39,300
in the i basis, so this is i equals 1,

2306
01:30:39,300 --> 01:30:41,300
i equals 2, i equals 3, i equals 4,

2307
01:30:41,300 --> 01:30:43,300
likewise with the rows.

2308
01:30:43,300 --> 01:30:45,300
It's going to be a diagonal matrix,

2309
01:30:45,300 --> 01:30:48,300
and its entries are just going to be rho.

2310
01:30:48,300 --> 01:30:50,300
Rho 1, rho 2, on the diagonal,

2311
01:30:50,300 --> 01:30:53,300
rho 1, rho 2, rho 3.

2312
01:31:02,300 --> 01:31:05,300
All other elements zero.

2313
01:31:06,300 --> 01:31:13,300
The rows are real numbers,

2314
01:31:13,300 --> 01:31:15,300
they're positive numbers because they're probabilities,

2315
01:31:15,300 --> 01:31:17,300
and they're all less than 1.

2316
01:31:17,300 --> 01:31:20,300
And one more thing, and this is called, incidentally,

2317
01:31:20,300 --> 01:31:23,300
this is called the density matrix.

2318
01:31:23,300 --> 01:31:28,300
It's called rho, and it's called the density matrix.

2319
01:31:28,300 --> 01:31:30,800
It's the analog in classical

2320
01:31:30,800 --> 01:31:33,300
physics of the probability density,

2321
01:31:33,300 --> 01:31:35,300
what we call p sub i.

2322
01:31:35,300 --> 01:31:39,300
But it's now just been organized into a matrix

2323
01:31:39,300 --> 01:31:41,300
with diagonal matrix elements.

2324
01:31:41,300 --> 01:31:44,300
The elements are all real,

2325
01:31:44,300 --> 01:31:48,300
and obviously they are the eigenvalues of this matrix,

2326
01:31:48,300 --> 01:31:52,300
because whenever a matrix has been written in diagonal form,

2327
01:31:52,300 --> 01:31:55,300
the diagonal elements are its eigenvalues.

2328
01:31:55,300 --> 01:31:57,300
One more thing you can say,

2329
01:31:57,300 --> 01:32:00,300
the trace of the density matrix is 1.

2330
01:32:00,300 --> 01:32:01,300
Why is that?

2331
01:32:01,300 --> 01:32:04,300
Because probabilities should add up to 1.

2332
01:32:04,300 --> 01:32:05,800
So if the sum of all

2333
01:32:05,800 --> 01:32:07,300
the probabilities adds up to 1,

2334
01:32:07,300 --> 01:32:08,800
then the trace of the

2335
01:32:08,800 --> 01:32:10,300
density matrix adds up to 1.

2336
01:32:25,300 --> 01:32:27,300
Now, let's suppose we have some observable.

2337
01:32:27,300 --> 01:32:30,300
Let's call the observable F.

2338
01:32:30,300 --> 01:32:32,300
And it's also a Hermitian operator.

2339
01:32:34,300 --> 01:32:55,300
Well, we have an observable F.

2340
01:32:55,300 --> 01:32:58,300
It's a Hermitian operator, as always.

2341
01:32:58,300 --> 01:33:01,300
Let me define now the average value of F.

2342
01:33:01,300 --> 01:33:03,300
If we had an ordinary state, in other words,

2343
01:33:03,300 --> 01:33:05,300
if we knew which state

2344
01:33:05,300 --> 01:33:07,300
we were in with probability 1,

2345
01:33:07,300 --> 01:33:10,300
then the average of F would just be

2346
01:33:10,300 --> 01:33:14,300
the expectation value of F in that state.

2347
01:33:14,300 --> 01:33:16,300
If we were in the i-th state,

2348
01:33:16,300 --> 01:33:18,300
the average of F would just

2349
01:33:18,300 --> 01:33:20,300
be the expectation value of F.

2350
01:33:20,300 --> 01:33:23,300
That's obvious, right?

2351
01:33:23,300 --> 01:33:24,300
All right.

2352
01:33:24,300 --> 01:33:25,300
I say more generally,

2353
01:33:25,300 --> 01:33:29,300
when you have this uncertainty about which state you're in,

2354
01:33:29,300 --> 01:33:31,300
that the right answer is that the average of F,

2355
01:33:31,300 --> 01:33:33,300
I won't indicate it the same way,

2356
01:33:33,300 --> 01:33:35,300
I won't indicate it by a bra and a ket,

2357
01:33:35,300 --> 01:33:37,300
because it's implicit in that

2358
01:33:37,300 --> 01:33:39,300
that I have a particular state.

2359
01:33:39,300 --> 01:33:43,300
I'll just write it as the average of F

2360
01:33:43,300 --> 01:33:46,300
is equal to the trace of

2361
01:33:46,300 --> 01:33:49,300
the product of F and rho.

2362
01:33:53,300 --> 01:33:54,800
Let's see if we can make

2363
01:33:54,800 --> 01:33:56,300
any sense out of that formula.

2364
01:33:56,300 --> 01:33:58,300
That formula is quite similar

2365
01:33:58,300 --> 01:34:01,300
to the corresponding classical formula,

2366
01:34:01,300 --> 01:34:03,300
summation over i,

2367
01:34:03,300 --> 01:34:07,300
of F sub i times P sub i.

2368
01:34:07,300 --> 01:34:09,300
Similar formula.

2369
01:34:09,300 --> 01:34:11,300
Trace being replaced,

2370
01:34:11,300 --> 01:34:14,300
or sum being replaced by trace,

2371
01:34:14,300 --> 01:34:18,300
classical function being replaced by an operator,

2372
01:34:18,300 --> 01:34:20,300
and the probability distribution being

2373
01:34:20,300 --> 01:34:22,300
replaced by the density matrix.

2374
01:34:22,300 --> 01:34:24,300
It's called density matrix

2375
01:34:24,300 --> 01:34:26,300
because it's like probability density.

2376
01:34:26,300 --> 01:34:28,300
Or probability, yeah.

2377
01:34:28,300 --> 01:34:31,300
Okay, let's work out what this thing is.

2378
01:34:31,300 --> 01:34:33,300
Let's work out what this thing is.

2379
01:34:33,300 --> 01:34:36,300
The trace, we can pick any basis we like,

2380
01:34:36,300 --> 01:34:38,300
but let's pick the basis in

2381
01:34:38,300 --> 01:34:40,300
which rho is diagonal for simplicity,

2382
01:34:40,300 --> 01:34:43,300
assuming that rho is diagonal in some basis.

2383
01:34:43,300 --> 01:34:46,300
Then this just becomes, the trace tells us,

2384
01:34:46,300 --> 01:34:48,300
where's the definition of the trace?

2385
01:34:48,300 --> 01:34:52,300
The trace tells us to take the basis,

2386
01:34:52,300 --> 01:34:54,300
take the thing whose trace we're taking,

2387
01:34:54,300 --> 01:34:56,300
F times rho,

2388
01:34:56,300 --> 01:34:58,300
and close it up again,

2389
01:34:58,300 --> 01:35:01,300
and sum over i.

2390
01:35:01,300 --> 01:35:05,300
That's the trace of F times rho.

2391
01:35:05,300 --> 01:35:07,300
Okay, now I'm going to do a

2392
01:35:07,300 --> 01:35:09,300
trick which we talked about last time,

2393
01:35:09,300 --> 01:35:11,300
we never really used very much,

2394
01:35:11,300 --> 01:35:13,300
but I'm going to use it now.

2395
01:35:13,300 --> 01:35:15,300
If we have a basis of states,

2396
01:35:15,300 --> 01:35:18,300
then the unit operator can be represented

2397
01:35:18,300 --> 01:35:23,300
as the sum over the states of

2398
01:35:23,300 --> 01:35:27,300
the dyads made up out of the basis vectors.

2399
01:35:27,300 --> 01:35:31,300
So let's, and what this means is you can always

2400
01:35:31,300 --> 01:35:33,300
stick an expression like this

2401
01:35:33,300 --> 01:35:35,300
between anything else

2402
01:35:35,300 --> 01:35:36,300
and not change it.

2403
01:35:36,300 --> 01:35:37,800
So in particular, I'm going to

2404
01:35:37,800 --> 01:35:39,300
stick it between F and rho.

2405
01:35:39,300 --> 01:35:40,800
Alright, so that'll give us, now

2406
01:35:40,800 --> 01:35:42,300
we have two sums to do,

2407
01:35:42,300 --> 01:35:45,300
one for the definition of the trace,

2408
01:35:45,300 --> 01:35:47,300
and one for resolving the identity.

2409
01:35:47,300 --> 01:35:49,300
This is called resolving the identity

2410
01:35:49,300 --> 01:35:52,300
by using a complete basis of states.

2411
01:35:52,300 --> 01:35:56,300
So that would give us

2412
01:35:56,300 --> 01:36:00,300
i, F, j, j, rho, i,

2413
01:36:00,300 --> 01:36:04,300
summed not only over i, but also over j.

2414
01:36:04,300 --> 01:36:06,300
Summed over i for the trace,

2415
01:36:06,300 --> 01:36:09,300
summed over j to resolve the identity.

2416
01:36:09,300 --> 01:36:16,300
Good, now, rho, in the basis that I'm using,

2417
01:36:16,300 --> 01:36:18,300
I'm assuming is diagonal.

2418
01:36:18,300 --> 01:36:21,300
That means that i has to equal j,

2419
01:36:21,300 --> 01:36:23,300
otherwise we don't get an expression.

2420
01:36:23,300 --> 01:36:26,300
Alright, in that case, this just becomes

2421
01:36:26,300 --> 01:36:29,300
the ijth matrix element, sorry,

2422
01:36:29,300 --> 01:36:30,300
the diagonal matrix element.

2423
01:36:30,300 --> 01:36:33,300
So this is the diagonal matrix element of rho.

2424
01:36:33,300 --> 01:36:35,300
i has to equal j.

2425
01:36:35,300 --> 01:36:38,300
We'll get nothing unless i equals j.

2426
01:36:38,300 --> 01:36:41,300
This just becomes rho sub i,

2427
01:36:41,300 --> 01:36:43,300
the i-th entry into the matrix,

2428
01:36:43,300 --> 01:36:49,300
and this becomes Fii.

2429
01:36:49,300 --> 01:36:51,300
Well, what is this?

2430
01:36:51,300 --> 01:36:52,800
This is the expectation value

2431
01:36:52,800 --> 01:36:54,300
of F in the state i.

2432
01:36:54,300 --> 01:36:59,300
This is the probability that the state was made

2433
01:36:59,300 --> 01:37:01,300
in configuration i.

2434
01:37:01,300 --> 01:37:03,300
And this is just the sum

2435
01:37:03,300 --> 01:37:05,300
of the expectation values of F

2436
01:37:05,300 --> 01:37:08,300
weighted with the probability distribution

2437
01:37:08,300 --> 01:37:10,300
for different states.

2438
01:37:10,300 --> 01:37:11,300
Okay?

2439
01:37:11,300 --> 01:37:13,300
So this makes sense to

2440
01:37:13,300 --> 01:37:15,300
call this the average of F.

2441
01:37:15,300 --> 01:37:20,300
But we see now a quantum mechanical version

2442
01:37:20,300 --> 01:37:23,300
of this formula over here,

2443
01:37:23,300 --> 01:37:28,300
in which, as I said, sum is replaced by trace,

2444
01:37:28,300 --> 01:37:32,300
and probability distribution is replaced by rho.

2445
01:37:36,300 --> 01:37:38,300
Here's a little theorem that you can prove.

2446
01:37:38,300 --> 01:37:40,300
It takes two seconds to prove.

2447
01:37:40,300 --> 01:37:42,300
If you have the product of two operators,

2448
01:37:42,300 --> 01:37:44,300
a and b,

2449
01:37:44,300 --> 01:37:46,300
the trace of a times b

2450
01:37:46,300 --> 01:37:49,300
is the same as the trace of b times a.

2451
01:37:49,300 --> 01:37:51,300
Work that out.

2452
01:37:51,300 --> 01:37:53,300
Even if a and b don't commute,

2453
01:37:53,300 --> 01:37:55,300
the trace of the product,

2454
01:37:55,300 --> 01:37:57,300
doesn't matter which way you order them,

2455
01:37:57,300 --> 01:37:59,300
and so in fact it doesn't matter

2456
01:37:59,300 --> 01:38:01,300
which way you order F and rho,

2457
01:38:01,300 --> 01:38:05,300
trace of F times rho is the average.

2458
01:38:05,300 --> 01:38:07,300
Okay.

2459
01:38:07,300 --> 01:38:13,300
That gives us the concept of a density matrix.

2460
01:38:13,300 --> 01:38:17,300
Let's just look at some analogies with P.

2461
01:38:17,300 --> 01:38:21,300
First of all, the sum of P sub i

2462
01:38:21,300 --> 01:38:23,300
should equal one.

2463
01:38:23,300 --> 01:38:25,300
The analog is that the trace,

2464
01:38:25,300 --> 01:38:29,300
is that the trace of rho is equal to one.

2465
01:38:29,300 --> 01:38:33,300
Trace of rho is equal to one.

2466
01:38:33,300 --> 01:38:41,300
So that's just another example of trace

2467
01:38:41,300 --> 01:38:45,300
and sum being essentially the same thing.

2468
01:38:45,300 --> 01:38:47,300
Good.

2469
01:38:47,300 --> 01:38:49,300
Now I'm going to give you the concept,

2470
01:38:49,300 --> 01:38:51,300
the quantum mechanical concept of entropy.

2471
01:38:51,300 --> 01:38:53,300
This is the quantum mechanical entropy,

2472
01:38:53,300 --> 01:38:55,300
and it's called the quantum mechanical entropy.

2473
01:38:55,300 --> 01:38:59,300
The entropy of a given density matrix.

2474
01:38:59,300 --> 01:39:02,300
Now first of all, the definition is such,

2475
01:39:02,300 --> 01:39:04,300
that if you know what state you're in,

2476
01:39:04,300 --> 01:39:06,300
only one of these rows is one,

2477
01:39:06,300 --> 01:39:08,300
and all the others are zero,

2478
01:39:08,300 --> 01:39:10,300
then the entropy is zero.

2479
01:39:10,300 --> 01:39:12,300
For any quantum mechanical state,

2480
01:39:12,300 --> 01:39:15,300
any real quantum mechanical state of the usual kind,

2481
01:39:15,300 --> 01:39:17,300
the entropy is zero.

2482
01:39:17,300 --> 01:39:20,300
The entropy is not zero,

2483
01:39:20,300 --> 01:39:22,300
not because quantum mechanics has in it

2484
01:39:22,300 --> 01:39:24,300
a built-in probabilistic aspect,

2485
01:39:24,300 --> 01:39:26,300
but because you simply didn't know

2486
01:39:26,300 --> 01:39:28,300
what state the system was made in.

2487
01:39:28,300 --> 01:39:30,300
You weren't told.

2488
01:39:30,300 --> 01:39:34,300
That's the source of entropy in quantum mechanics,

2489
01:39:34,300 --> 01:39:36,300
lack of knowledge about the state,

2490
01:39:36,300 --> 01:39:38,300
not lack of knowledge even if you knew the state.

2491
01:39:38,300 --> 01:39:41,300
Okay, the answer for the entropy,

2492
01:39:41,300 --> 01:39:43,300
the definition of the entropy,

2493
01:39:43,300 --> 01:39:45,300
given a density matrix rho,

2494
01:39:45,300 --> 01:39:47,300
first of all, here's how you use it

2495
01:39:47,300 --> 01:39:49,300
to calculate averages,

2496
01:39:49,300 --> 01:39:51,300
but second of all,

2497
01:39:51,300 --> 01:39:53,300
the definition of the density matrix,

2498
01:39:53,300 --> 01:39:56,300
well, let's first write down the classical formula.

2499
01:39:56,300 --> 01:39:58,300
The classical formula was sum on i

2500
01:39:58,300 --> 01:40:04,300
minus of p sub i log p sub i.

2501
01:40:04,300 --> 01:40:06,300
Well, the answer is trace,

2502
01:40:06,300 --> 01:40:11,300
minus the trace of the density matrix rho

2503
01:40:11,300 --> 01:40:15,300
times the logarithm of the density matrix rho.

2504
01:40:15,300 --> 01:40:20,300
What the hell is logarithm of a matrix anyway?

2505
01:40:20,300 --> 01:40:23,300
Well, there's a general answer to that.

2506
01:40:23,300 --> 01:40:24,800
But let me give you

2507
01:40:24,800 --> 01:40:26,300
the answer in the simple case

2508
01:40:26,300 --> 01:40:29,300
where the matrix can be brought to a diagonal form.

2509
01:40:29,300 --> 01:40:32,300
If the matrix in some basis is diagonal,

2510
01:40:32,300 --> 01:40:35,300
then the logarithm of the matrix

2511
01:40:35,300 --> 01:40:37,300
is just the matrix made out of the logarithms

2512
01:40:37,300 --> 01:40:40,300
of the eigenvalues.

2513
01:40:40,300 --> 01:40:44,300
Log of rho,

2514
01:40:44,300 --> 01:40:46,300
log rho one,

2515
01:40:46,300 --> 01:40:48,300
log rho two,

2516
01:40:48,300 --> 01:40:51,300
and so forth and so on.

2517
01:40:51,300 --> 01:40:52,300
All right.

2518
01:40:52,300 --> 01:40:54,300
So what is this?

2519
01:40:54,300 --> 01:40:55,300
This is, of course,

2520
01:40:55,300 --> 01:40:57,300
just the sum of the rho

2521
01:40:57,300 --> 01:40:59,300
sub i's log rho sub i's,

2522
01:40:59,300 --> 01:41:01,300
exactly as it is classically,

2523
01:41:01,300 --> 01:41:04,300
but I've written it in a form now

2524
01:41:04,300 --> 01:41:11,300
that is more appropriate for quantum mechanics

2525
01:41:11,300 --> 01:41:14,300
as the trace of rho log rho,

2526
01:41:14,300 --> 01:41:16,300
and so it has meaning in a vector space,

2527
01:41:16,300 --> 01:41:20,300
not just as a classical probability distribution.

2528
01:41:20,300 --> 01:41:23,300
So what is the definition of the entropy?

2529
01:41:23,300 --> 01:41:25,300
It has the property

2530
01:41:25,300 --> 01:41:27,300
that if only one and only

2531
01:41:27,300 --> 01:41:29,300
one of the rows are non-zero,

2532
01:41:29,300 --> 01:41:31,300
in which case it has to be one,

2533
01:41:31,300 --> 01:41:33,300
because the trace of rho has to be one,

2534
01:41:33,300 --> 01:41:36,300
if one and only one of them is non-zero,

2535
01:41:36,300 --> 01:41:39,300
then the entropy is zero.

2536
01:41:39,300 --> 01:41:40,300
Okay?

2537
01:41:40,300 --> 01:41:43,300
One times log of one is equal to zero.

2538
01:41:43,300 --> 01:41:46,300
If the probability distribution is uniform,

2539
01:41:46,300 --> 01:41:48,300
all states having equal probability,

2540
01:41:48,300 --> 01:41:50,300
that would be the case where this would be

2541
01:41:50,300 --> 01:41:52,300
proportional to the unit matrix,

2542
01:41:52,300 --> 01:41:55,300
then the entropy here is logarithm

2543
01:41:55,300 --> 01:41:57,300
of the number of states,

2544
01:41:57,300 --> 01:42:01,300
logarithm of the dimensionality of the space of states.

2545
01:42:01,300 --> 01:42:03,300
So if you know nothing about the system,

2546
01:42:03,300 --> 01:42:05,300
you don't know how it was prepared,

2547
01:42:05,300 --> 01:42:06,300
or anything like that,

2548
01:42:06,300 --> 01:42:09,300
then the entropy is just logarithm

2549
01:42:09,300 --> 01:42:11,300
of the total number of states,

2550
01:42:11,300 --> 01:42:13,300
which means the logarithm of the space of states,

2551
01:42:13,300 --> 01:42:16,300
logarithm of the dimension of the space of states,

2552
01:42:16,300 --> 01:42:19,300
and that's taking over

2553
01:42:19,300 --> 01:42:22,300
practically directly

2554
01:42:22,300 --> 01:42:25,300
from the classical concept of entropy,

2555
01:42:25,300 --> 01:42:27,300
and it plays the same role.

2556
01:42:27,300 --> 01:42:31,300
It's an indication of lack of knowledge of the system,

2557
01:42:31,300 --> 01:42:33,300
knowledge that you could have,

2558
01:42:33,300 --> 01:42:35,300
but that you don't have.

2559
01:42:35,300 --> 01:42:37,300
In other words, the knowledge

2560
01:42:37,300 --> 01:42:39,300
that is there to be gotten,

2561
01:42:39,300 --> 01:42:44,300
but which you may have been too lazy to get.

2562
01:42:44,300 --> 01:42:47,300
What's all of this have to do with entanglement?

2563
01:42:47,300 --> 01:42:48,300
Well, I think we're going to

2564
01:42:48,300 --> 01:42:49,300
have to do a little bit more

2565
01:42:49,300 --> 01:42:50,300
of that,

2566
01:42:50,300 --> 01:42:52,300
and I'm going to have to quit now.

2567
01:42:52,300 --> 01:42:54,300
Next time, I'm going to show you

2568
01:42:54,300 --> 01:42:56,300
what this has to do with entanglement,

2569
01:42:56,300 --> 01:42:58,300
but basically I'll just outline it for you.

2570
01:42:58,300 --> 01:42:59,800
When you have a system

2571
01:42:59,800 --> 01:43:01,300
which is composed of many parts,

2572
01:43:01,300 --> 01:43:05,300
or let's say two parts to be specific,

2573
01:43:05,300 --> 01:43:08,300
you may be interested in only one of the parts

2574
01:43:08,300 --> 01:43:10,300
and not look at the other part.

2575
01:43:10,300 --> 01:43:14,300
You may have a system

2576
01:43:14,300 --> 01:43:17,300
which consists of two entangled parts,

2577
01:43:17,300 --> 01:43:19,300
they may or may not be entangled,

2578
01:43:19,300 --> 01:43:22,300
in particular it's interesting when they are entangled,

2579
01:43:22,300 --> 01:43:24,300
A and B,

2580
01:43:24,300 --> 01:43:27,300
they're in some state which is an entangled state

2581
01:43:27,300 --> 01:43:29,300
of the two systems,

2582
01:43:29,300 --> 01:43:32,300
but you're only going to do experiments on A

2583
01:43:32,300 --> 01:43:35,300
and ignore B altogether.

2584
01:43:35,300 --> 01:43:38,300
Then the question is how do you describe A

2585
01:43:38,300 --> 01:43:40,300
without reference to B?

2586
01:43:40,300 --> 01:43:43,300
There must be some description that you can use

2587
01:43:43,300 --> 01:43:48,300
for A which contains all possible experimental

2588
01:43:48,300 --> 01:43:51,300
information that you could do on A

2589
01:43:51,300 --> 01:43:54,300
if you're never interested in also looking at B,

2590
01:43:54,300 --> 01:43:56,300
if you don't look at B.

2591
01:43:56,300 --> 01:43:58,300
And the answer is you use

2592
01:43:58,300 --> 01:44:00,300
a density matrix to describe A.

2593
01:44:00,300 --> 01:44:03,300
If A and B are entangled,

2594
01:44:03,300 --> 01:44:06,300
then the density matrix will have entropy.

2595
01:44:06,300 --> 01:44:08,300
If A and B are not entangled,

2596
01:44:08,300 --> 01:44:10,300
it will not have entropy.

2597
01:44:10,300 --> 01:44:15,300
So one diagnostic for looking at a system

2598
01:44:15,300 --> 01:44:17,300
or at a composite system

2599
01:44:17,300 --> 01:44:19,300
to find out if things are entangled

2600
01:44:19,300 --> 01:44:22,300
is to determine what's called

2601
01:44:22,300 --> 01:44:25,300
the entanglement entropy of the two systems.

2602
01:44:25,300 --> 01:44:28,300
And it's a measure of how badly entangled they are.

2603
01:44:28,300 --> 01:44:29,300
We'll come to it next

2604
01:44:29,300 --> 01:44:30,300
time and we'll work it out.

2605
01:44:30,300 --> 01:44:32,300
And we'll work out some examples.

2606
01:44:32,300 --> 01:44:35,300
I want to work out some real examples

2607
01:44:35,300 --> 01:44:37,300
to show you how entanglement entropy

2608
01:44:37,300 --> 01:44:40,300
codes the fact that systems are entangled.

